This file is an exploratory analysis of the effect of climate-induced shifts in angler catch-per-trip of Gulf of Maine cod and haddock. Results are based on 100 iterations of the recreation demand model. The RDM is calibrated to 2020 fishery conditions.

Decadal bottom temp trends

Mean monthly bottom temps by decade, red line indicates decadal average. Bars represent mean monthly temp +/- 1.96*standard dev.

Projected differences in average monthly sea bottom temperatures relative to 2020. Bars represent lower and upper bounds of the projected average monthly temperatures. Red lines indicate differences between the decadal and 2020 annual average.

Baseline welfare calculations

After calibrating the simulation model to 2020 fishery conditions, I re-ran the model under two closure scenarios: (a) bag limits for both cod and haddock set to zero, and (b) bag limits for cod only set to zero.

Historical projected fishery outcomes

From Jorge’s notes: we will run the bioeconomic model for each of the years in the period 2010-2019 as follows: i) calibrate the model for year 201X, ii) predict year 201X+1 under independent and dependent catch-per trip for cod and haddock, then calibrate year 201X+1 and predict 201X+2 , and so forth. Jorge will generate the catch-per-trip data for each year for both the independent and correlated scenarios as follows: i) use the biomass and ocean bottom temperatures for each year in 2010-2019 to calculate the expect catch-per-trip for cod and haddock, ii) add to the expect catch-per-trip the simulated residuals (correlated or independent) to generate the independent and correlated samples to use in the simulations.

I’ve included a plot of “bag limit potential” by species to visualize the stringency of regulations. To create this variable, I multiply the number of trips in 201X by season by the bag limit in 201X+1. In cases where the haddock bag limit was unlimited, I set the bag limit to 20 given the highest observed haddock bag limit over the series was 15. While size limits do change over the period, the model does not account for account for this. Instead, it implicitly assumes that the proportion of legal-size fish in the prediction year is the same as the proportion of legal-size fish in the calibration year. This is an issue we may want to revisit and correct for. \(~\)
